         <lb/>
         <lb/>
         <head>NOTES <hi rend="small">TO THE </hi>POEM <hi rend="small">OF </hi>
                              MICHAEL.</head>
         <div xml:id="note1m">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">note i. </hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note"> Page 213—line 14 “There’s Richard
                                   Bateman,” &amp;c. The <lb/>story alluded to here is well
                                   known in the country. The <lb/>chapel is called Ings Chapel ; and
                                   is on the right hand side <lb/>of the road leading from Kendal to
                                   Ambleside.</p>
         </div>
         <lb/>
         <div xml:id="note2m">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">note ii.</hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note"> Page 217—line 4 “ ———had
                                   design’d to build a sheep-<lb/>fold.” &amp;c. It may
                                   be proper to inform some readers, that a <lb/>sheep-fold in these
                                   mountains is an unroofed building of stone <lb/>walls, with
                                   different divisions. It is generally placed by the <lb/>side of a
                                   brook, for the convenience of washing the sheep ; <lb/>but it is
                                   also useful as a shelter for them, and as a place to <lb/>drive
                                   them into, to enable the shepherds conveniently to <lb/>single
                                   out one or more for any particular purpose.</p>
            <lb/>
         </div>
         <trailer>
            <hi rend="bold">END. </hi>
         </trailer>
      </body>
